sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM command_comments 
WHERE TRIM(comment) <> 'None';

SELECT simulation_name, description
FROM simulations
WHERE simulation_id = '0';

SELECT DISTINCT simulation_id
FROM commands
WHERE status = 'active';

external_knowledge:
- This question assumes that "comprehensive command details" include command identifiers, sequences, creation and update timestamps, statuses, versions, and descriptions; 
- "Hierarchy" refers to the structure of commands based on their parent-child relationships; 
- "Creation and update information" includes data about the users who created and last updated the commands, along with the timestamps of these actions; 
- "Associated user data" refers to the usernames and email addresses of the creators and updaters; 
- "Simulation details" include the names, descriptions, statuses, and versions of the simulations with which the commands are associated; 
- "Change history" pertains to the descriptions and dates of changes made to the commands; 
- "Running count of commands within each simulation" is a cumulative count of commands ordered by their sequence within each simulation.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(command_id) AS total_commands_with_sequence_order
FROM command_sequence
WHERE sequence_order = 1;

SELECT command_id
   FROM command_sequence
   WHERE sequence_order = (SELECT MIN(sequence_order) FROM command_sequence);

external_knowledge:
Command hierarchy refers to a structure where commands are nested within each other, indicating parent-child relationships; 
A command's level in the hierarchy represents its depth within this structure, starting from 1 for top-level commands; 
A command's sequence indicates its order relative to its siblings in the hierarchy; 
Command status reflects whether the command is active or not; 
Distinct command identities mean that each command is represented only once in the results, even if it appears multiple times in the database due to different comments or change dates.
